Former head of Brazilian presidential cabinet brought before court
On Tuesday, a federal judge accepted accusations against the former head of Brazil’s presidential cabinet for his alleged involvement in a massive corruption scheme over state-owned oil company Petrobras.
The federal prosecutor’s office said Jose Dirceu would be sued over allegations of corruption, fraud and money laundering this month.
Fourteen others will be tried, including Joao Vaccari Neto, the former treasurer of Brazil’s ruling Workers’ Party, and Renato de Souza Duque, the former president of Petrobras’ business services.
Dirceu is the oldest member of the ruling Workers’ Party taken into custody for ties to this scheme.
Dirceu served as chief of staff to former President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva between 2003 and 2005.
He was arrested in early August from home, where he was already under house arrest, with an 11-year sentence for involvement in a vote-buying scheme in Congress more than 10 years ago.
Prosecutors said Dirceu developed Petrobras’ bribery scheme, accepted bribes while in office, and continued to receive payments from entrepreneurs after it was shut down in late 2013 for the vote-bought scandal.
According to prosecutors, the Petrobras scheme involved about $2 billion in bribes and other illegal funds.
Some of that money would have returned to the campaign fund of the ruling party and its allies.
It would also include bribes to Petrobras executives in exchange for inflated contracts.
“Miracle” Recovery of a Survivor of the Peshawar Massacre
A paralyzed teenager after being shot four times in Pakistan's worst terrorist attack has achieved a "miraculous" recovery after undergoing treatment in the United Kingdom.
13-year-old Mohamed Ibrahim Khan had been told by doctors in Pakistan that he would never be able to walk again.
At least 140 people, mostly children, were killed when gunmen attacked the army’s public school in Peshawar last December.
Mohamed, who arrived in London last month for surgery, will later be discharged from the hospital.
Exactly nine months ago, on an ordinary Tuesday morning, Mohamed stood at first aid and listened carefully to his teachers.
Even then, many armed men disguised in the uniforms of security guards entered the army’s public school.
They wore explosive belts and had a simple mission: to kill all the men, women, and children who stood in their way.
“I can’t forget what happened that day,” Mohamed said with a sharp glance.
I was sitting in the amphitheatre, asking questions... and then I heard gunshots outside.
The terrorists went inside and started killing. Our teacher was burned alive.
Mohamed describes how he pulled four students out of the amphitheater while the carnage unfolded.
Then he says he heard his friend, Hamza, yelling at him.
He said, "Oh, brother, save me."
I held his hand.
Then I was shot in the back, and he in the head.
Most of those killed in the attack were students.
Hamza died in Mohamed's arms.
Mohamed recalls that immediately after this he fainted and that the next thing he knew was that he was on a hospital bed, paralyzed from the waist down.
Doctors in Peshawar in northern Pakistan, then in Rawalpindi, near the capital, told his family that there was no treatment and that he would never be able to walk again.
“When I saw him, I felt my soul come out,” said Mohamed’s father, Sher Khan.
Those nine months were the hardest of my life.
But Khan and his wife, Sherbano, refused to believe that their son, who is so passionate about cricket, would ever be able to use his feet again.
They campaigned and sought help from Pakistani television, drawing support from famous people like Imran Khan, a cricketer turned politician.
Eventually, they were able to raise funds to take Mohamed to the UK and offer him treatment at the Harley Street private clinic in London.
Consultant neurosurgeon Irfan Malik described Mohamed as "afraid" when he arrived at the hospital.
“He had spent the last [several] months lying in bed, unable to move from one side to the other,” Malik says.
He was weak, put a lot of pressure on his back.
He wasn't in very good shape.
A vertebra at the base of Mohamed's spine had been destroyed.
Mohamed had been shot in the shoulder, hip and back during the attack, and his lower spine had been destroyed, leading to paralysis.
However, during a six-hour operation, Malik and his team were able to reconnect the nerve endings and rebuild the damaged part of the spine.
Even Malik was surprised by what happened next.
Exactly a week after the surgery, Mohamed got up and started taking steps and walking.
We did not expect such a good result.
It was a miracle,” he says.
Within two weeks of the operation, Mohamed is ready to leave the hospital and begin the long recovery process.
Mohammed defied fate and began to walk again.
He wants to become strong and continue his studies in the UK.
But he is determined to return to Pakistan, enlist in the military and fight terrorism.
“I feel like I have another chance at life,” he says, showing pictures of guns drawn by him next to school textbooks and pens.
Physically, Mohamed is getting stronger every day, but the psychological trauma he is going through is unimaginable.
“My anger has not diminished,” he confesses.
In my school, young children were killed.
What crime did they commit?
His mother wipes a tear, comforts the child and says, “I see my son walking again.”
He will be able to continue his natural life.
The 4G “Super Voice” service from Three provides a better signal
Three uses a lower-frequency 4G spectrum that can cover a wider area
Mobile phone provider Three has launched a service in the UK that it says will improve reception inside buildings and in rural areas without a signal.
The 4G Super Voice service allows customers to make calls and send text messages using a lower frequency spectrum.
Other networks are also planning to introduce the same technology, known as "Voice Over Long-Term Evolution (VoLTE)".
It only works with the Samsung Galaxy S5 at the moment, but recent iPhones will benefit from it in the coming months.
Three says up to 5.5 million customers will have access to the service by 2017.
Chief Technology Officer Bryn Jones said: “By the end of the year, one million of our customers will have access to better indoor coverage and will be able to use their phones in more places than ever before.”
