Steven Wilson: “If I don’t do anything, I feel guilty.”
Steven Wilson was named the winner of the Progressive Music Awards.
Steven Wilson has often been named the most hard-working musician in the world of progressive rock.
The talented musician won three awards at the Progressive Music Awards, which took place this month in London, including the Best Album of the Year award for Hand.
In its five-star review, The Guardian called the album “a smart, expressive and captivating work of art.”
Since the 1980s, Wilson has been the driving force behind several musical projects, the most famous of which is the rock band Porcupine Tree.
Now, ahead of two closed house performances at Royal Albert Hall, Wilson releases a vinyl-only double LP, Transition, to showcase the “more affordable” side of his solo activity.
He told the BBC about his love of vinyl and his busy schedule and explained how comedian Matt Berry ended up opening his shows.
What does vinyl mean to you?
I grew up right at the end of the vinyl era and I remember that at the time I was looking forward to the CD, because vinyl was so annoying.
You bought a record, went home with him, had a scratch, and you had to bring it back.
I love CDs, and for certain types of music, for example classical music, they’re better than vinyl.
But the problem with CDs and digital downloads is that there’s nothing else you really value.
Having a vinyl is like having a beautiful painting hanging in the living room.
It’s something you can hold in your hand as you get absorbed in lyrics and overwhelmed by the artistic act.
I thought it was just a nostalgic thing, but it can’t be understood if some kids too young to remember vinyls like that kind of experience.
Do you have any vinyl that you particularly care about?
I admit I got rid of all the vinyl in the '90s.
All the vinyls I have are bought again.
I started with the idea of redoing the collection I had at 15, but I crossed that limit.
The first album I ever bought was Out of the Blue by the Electric Light Orchestra.
If I still had the original, it would have had sentimental value, but, unfortunately, it’s somewhere through a charity store.
Steven Wilson hopes the album will be a gateway to potential new fans
Why did you release your new Transience compilation on vinyl?
It was originally conceived as an idea for Record Store Day, but we missed the opportunity.
My record company had suggested that I collect some of my shorter and more accessible songs.
I became slightly obsessed with the idea of doing something like “introducing Steven Wilson’s music” and I really wanted the project to be released only on vinyl.
Those who buy vinyl also get a high-resolution download version.
Are you worried that the album won’t show your music in its true light?
No, because although I focus on longer pieces of music, there is one thing I have always valued above all else: the melodic part.
There is a lot of progressive rock that focuses on technical complexity rather than on the melodic side.
Pink Floyd, the most famous progressive rock band of all time, have passed the test of time because they have always emphasized the melodic side and the atmosphere.
What are you doing at Albert Hall?
I don't want to reveal too much.
The repertoire will be completely different each night.
In the first, there will be a version of the show Hand. Erase. that we had this year, but on steroids, with a few guests.
The second night is going to be more of a foray into my history, and it’s more geared towards the fans who have followed me over the years.
How did you choose Matt Berry to open your show on the second night?
And me and the others on the tour team are big fans of the [Channel 4 comedy series] Toast of London, to the point where we always give quotes from it.
I thought about listening to Matt’s music, so I bought his album, Music for Insomniacs.
We talked to him about our mutual love for Mike Oldfield and asked him to sing at the Royal Albert Hall.
I think I'm extremely lucky to have him in the opening.
You've remixed albums from bands like XTC, Tears for Fears and Yes.
How much does that influence your music?
I’m not consciously inspired by this, but inevitably, when you deconstruct these classic albums, they stay in your mind.
My last solo album, The Raven That Refused to Sing, was arguably the most progressive old school album I’ve ever created.
I don’t think it was a coincidence that we had remixed King Crimson, Jethro Tull and Yes almost all the year before.
The current album, Hand. Erase., is much more open, because I had been working on Tears for Fears and XTC.
You are often described as the busiest progressive rock musician.
Do you know?
You can delete the word progressive.
I think I’m probably one of the most obsessed people in the music world today and I don’t say that with pride, because, please believe me, it’s a curse.
I think I inherited this from my father, who has an incredibly strong work ethic.
If I don't do anything for a whole day, I'm starting to feel guilty.
That’s why working on remixes was a gift, because it means I don’t have to do my music all the time.
The music industry is a tough place to make a career.
I wouldn’t recommend this to anyone as a profession.
I work every day and am not rich, but I live well.
I love what I do, it’s a privilege, but if I were lazy I don’t think I would have survived.
Transition will launch in the UK on September 25.
Steven Wilson will perform at the Royal Albert Hall on September 28 and 29 as part of his 2015-2016 European tour.
New contract brings jobs back to Skytrans
The new Skytrans has re-hired some of the airline’s staff who had lost their jobs when the old Skytrans went bankrupt.
Skytrans, the refurbished company in northern Queensland, has been awarded a $25 million contract to transport gas company QGC employees, which means 18 crew members have regained their jobs.
Skytrans, a Wild family-owned company, became very active in January after the Newman government rewarded subsidized routes that made up much of the airline’s business.
Bankruptcy caused more communities to face potential isolation, and Warren Entsch, a federal and liberal lawmaker for Northern Queensland, was the voice of critics of the national-liberal government.
Another company, Collings Aircraft Holdings, relaunched the Skytrans brand in March.
Michael Thinee, chief executive of Skytrans, said the airline’s contract with QCG has already created jobs.
“We have managed to re-hire 18 full-time Skytrans personnel as pilots and crew members,” he said.
We are also delighted to have new staff with direct logistics experience in managing flight operations for QGC customers.
In just five months, we have increased our workforce by 100%, with 78 staff employed in Cairns and now in Brisbane.
The contract aims for Skytrans to expand its flight operations from its headquarters in Cairns, which serves Cape York and the Torres Strait, and to include a base in Brisbane.
Skytrans will operate 18 return flights per week for Brisbane HQC staff and entrepreneurs to Chinchilla and Taroom locations on its 36-seat Dash-8 aircraft starting Monday, October 26.
Tony Nunan, chief executive of the HQC, said Skytrans received the contract following an auction.
“We are delighted that this contract will contribute to the expansion of a Queensland company,” he said.
The Skytrans contract maintains its high quality and consistent flight services to support our operations and projects.
Liberal MP and fresh mom Kelly O'Dwyer gets advice to make a bigger reserve of milk to avoid missing votes in the House
There will be more women in the cabinet.
Malcolm Turnbull’s new government will be inaugurated on Monday and there are strong signals that more women will occupy the portfolios.
One of the government’s rising stars, Kelly O’Dwyer, has been advised to make a bigger reserve of milk for her newborn to avoid breastfeeding interfering in her duties in Parliament.
The advice comes from government discipline officer Scott Buchholz, who later consulted with his Labour counterpart to find out which approach is best for a nursing MP, according to the ordinances in place.
Liberal MP Kelly O'Dwyer with her daughter, Olivia.
According to the ordinances in force - the set of rules that govern the behavior of parliamentarians in the House - breastfeeding mothers get a power of vote in Parliament.
This means that their vote is considered valid even when they are not present in the Chamber.
But Whip didn’t know about this exemption before he consulted opposition discipline officer Chris Hayes on the issue.
Things rushed on two occasions when O'Dwyer could not attend a division meeting and could not fulfill his obligation to give a speech because he had just begun breastfeeding.
On one of these occasions, her team was asked if the MP was thinking of making a larger reserve of milk instead of breastfeeding.
Scott Buchholz, MP from Queensland, is in charge of government discipline.
Later, the two resolved their dispute.
Both declined to comment when they were contacted by Fairfax Media, but sources separate from Buchholz and O'Dwyer told Fairfax Media that the Higgins representative was furious when she was told to make a bigger reserve of milk instead of breastfeeding her daughter, Olivia, who was born in May.
This fact is revealed even as new Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull is working on building his new cabinet.
Buchholz, a liberal national lawmaker from Queensland, was promoted to the position of head of discipline by former Prime Minister Tony Abbott as part of the negative effect of this year’s February censorship attempt.
O'Dwyer, pictured alongside Labour's Amanda Rishworth and her son, Percy, is one of the three mothers in Parliament.
The ex-discipline officer, Phillip Ruddock, was removed just days after Abbott faced a no-confidence motion to remove him from office, and was replaced by Buchholz.
Another Abbott supporter, Andrew Nickolic, a Tasmanian liberal, was also promoted and appointed responsible for the deputy discipline.
Nickolic had lately been keeping the front page of the newspapers, after it was revealed that he had sent Turnbull a message asking him to give up the leadership of Abbott.
In August, O'Dwyer returned to Parliament for the first time since the birth of her daughter, Olivia, in May.
She is one of three women who became mothers this year.
Labour's spokeswoman Catherine King said on Wednesday that voting power for breastfeeding mothers was introduced when her son was a baby.
“She’s [seven years old] now,” she wrote on Twitter.
The discipline officer should have known.
O'Dwyer was promoted to the cabinet at the end of last year and can be promoted under the Turnbull, which said on Wednesday that it wants more women in its cabinet.
“No one wants to see more women in power, influence, in parliament, in ministries, across the country,” she told reporters.
Abbott included only one woman in his first cabinet and, after sustained pressure to increase female representation in the Coalition, promoted a second woman into the cabinet after the December reshuffle.
Five things the business environment wants from Prime Minister Malcolm Turnbull
Malcolm Turnbull: How will markets react?
Mal Maiden, an editor at BusinessDay, examines the impact Malcolm Turnbull could have on Australia’s business sector.
On Tuesday, business lobby groups didn’t know how to show their enthusiasm when Malcolm Turnbull took over the country’s reins as prime minister.
The main reason is that much of what many of them would have wanted to see had been abandoned under the leadership of Tony Abbott.
Or it had simply ended in a negotiated suspension because of Abbott's "crash-or-crash-through" political style.
Interest group representatives spoke in unison about their hope in Turnbull’s ability to satisfy the public interest, reach a political agreement, and do things right.
So what exactly are the country’s biggest companies and their representatives expecting from our new prime minister?
ChAFTA will be a first test of Turnbull’s ability to overcome negative publicity.
Turnbull himself set as a starting goal the free trade agreement with China.
In his first media speech announcing the challenge, the China-Australia Free Trade Agreement (ChAFTA) was the focal point of his attack on Labour leader Bill Shorten.
In an August speech, Turnbull criticized the Labour Party’s “disturbing outbursts of economic chauvinism” on the issue and expressed concern over the racist tempting of critics.
“In the Chafta context, the winners are, numerically, far more than the losers,” he said in the same speech.
The business community hopes he will win this debate.
Don Argus, the legendary representative of the business environment, stressed that this is a key point, being supported, among others, by the Australian Business Council (which represents the 100 largest companies in the country) and by James Packer, the billionaire in the gaming industry.
The business environment wants to conclude this deal, and this will be a first test of Turnbull’s ability to overcome negative publicity and negotiate with the entire Senate.
Small Business Minister Bruce Billson supports the recommendations of the Harper Analysis.
This could lead to some divergences with the business environment from the outset.
The impact assessment applies to large mergers and other contracts to decide whether consumers will suffer from lack of competition.
It is called “effect assessment” because it takes into account not only the actions and intentions of the company, but also the effect they will have on competition and the market.
The way this evaluation is written is extremely important for the outcome.
Harper’s analysis of competition law recommends a change in the assessment of the effects, which will make it harder for large corporations to ban smaller operators from the market.
The government led by Tony Abbott was on the side of the Australian Business Council and major retailers.
Turnbull now knows he wants the entire cabinet to think about what he’ll do next.
The CAA jumped to say that if Turnbull follows the recommendations of the Harper analysis, consumers will have to pay higher prices.
It’s ironic that the entire business community has advised the new prime minister to have greater respect for cabinet processes, which Turnbull seems to be doing by letting Bruce Billson, the small business minister (who is on Harper’s side) make his arguments in front of his colleagues.
