Terrence Howard is questioning the multiplication board.
Terrence Howard thinks I understand arithmetic completely.
The Empire villain told Rolling Stone magazine that he doesn’t believe that one or one is equal to one.
“How can it be equal to one?” he said.
If one or one makes one, it means that two has no value, since one or two itself has no effect.
One or one makes two, because the square root of four is two - so what is the square root of two?
There should be one, but we're told there are two, and that's impossible.
Terrence, we don't really understand what you mean.
Not surprisingly, Howard's professors disagreed with his theory, so he dropped out of the Pratt Institute, where he studied chemical engineering.
“You can’t close your eyes when you know something is wrong,” he said.
Howard found for his parallel approach to mathematics the name "Terryology".
The actor confesses that he spends his time cutting and reassembling scissors, wire, magnets and plastic sheets to illustrate his "one-time-one" theory and other similar theories.
He told the magazine that he and his ex-wife, Mira Pak, spent up to 17 hours a day creating these illustrations.
