New study shows more people die from air pollution than from malaria and HIV/AIDS
According to a new baseline study, more than 3 million people die prematurely from outdoor air pollution, less than from malaria and HIV/AIDS combined.
The main cause, especially in Asia, is burning wood and coal for home heating and cooking, but the research reveals that an equally alarming reason is agricultural emissions from Europe and the US, where they are the main cause of these deaths.
The report warns that if no action is taken, the number of deaths – already equivalent to six deaths per minute – will double by 2050.
“These projections should be a wake-up call for public health agencies around the world,” said Professor Michael Jerrett, an environmental health expert at the University of California, who was not involved in the research.
Most of the deaths caused by air rain are caused by tiny particles, which can be inhaled deep into the lungs.
They cause heart attack and stroke, which are responsible for three-quarters of the 3.3 million deaths annually, while the rest are caused by lung cancer and respiratory diseases.
The research did not include the effects of indoor air pollution, for example from cooking fires, which are estimated to cause another 3.4 million deaths per year.
The new study, published in the journal Nature, is the first to highlight various sources of outdoor air pollution and estimate the number of premature deaths they cause, taking into account road traffic, fossil-fuel power plants and other sources.
The researchers used a detailed computer model of the global atmosphere to assess the impact of air pollution on diverse populations, including new information about how pollution affects the inhabitants of China and India.
A third of all premature deaths were the result of the use of smoke-extracting fuels, such as wood and coal, for heating homes or cooking, and the use of dirty diesel generators for electricity, all of which are recognized hazards.
Consumption of this type of internal energy causes half of India’s 645,000 annual deaths and a third of China’s 1.4 million annual deaths.
But the research found that agricultural ammonia emissions had a “remarkable” impact, according to Professor Jos Lelieveld of the Max Planck Chemical Institute in Germany, who led the research.
One-fifth of deaths globally are caused by these emissions, which come mainly from cattle, poultry and pigs and from excess fertiliser use.
Ammonia reacts with exhaust gases from traffic and industry and produces tiny particles, being the main cause of death from air pollution in the eastern United States, Japan and Europe.
“For London, agriculture is the main source,” Lelieveld says.
Across the UK, 48% of premature deaths were the result of agricultural pollution.
Traffic pollution is still a major factor in developed countries, causing a fifth of deaths, despite measures against polluting vehicles.
This has caused only 5% of deaths globally, but the figure could rise as more cars appear on the streets in developing countries.
Air pollution from coal-fired power plants has been significant globally, causing one in seven deaths.
In the U.S., it is the main single factor, causing a third of the 55,000 deaths annually, compared to 16% in the United Kingdom.
Natural air pollution, especially in arid and dusty regions, has caused nearly one-fifth of the global deaths caused by air pollution.
This source is a major factor in some arid countries, accounting for 92% of deaths in Egypt and 81% in Iran.
“The overlap between the high pollution level and the high population speaks volumes about public health, but nothing is known about the sources of pollution responsible for premature deaths,” Jerrett says.
The results are surprising and potentially important for protecting public health globally.
It is now assumed that all particles are equally toxic.
But if fuel combustion is more toxic, as some scientists suspect, the percentage of premature deaths that can be attributed to agricultural emissions would be lower.
Even so, Jerrett says, “the discovery is very valuable...because agriculture has not generally been seen as a major source of air pollution or premature death and because it suggests that much more attention needs to be paid to agricultural sources, both by scientists and policymakers.”
Dr Oliver Wild, an atmospheric specialist at Lancaster University in the UK, said: “The study really underscores the need for air quality control to avoid these deaths, especially in heavily populated areas of Asia.”
