We are in a fishing race that could end up depriving people of a vital food source and an essential economic engine.
“Overfishing, destruction of marine habitats and climate change have serious consequences for the entire human population, and poor communities, which rely on the sea, will be hit the fastest and the strongest,” Lambertini said.
“The collapse of ocean ecosystems could trigger a serious economic decline and undermine our fight to eradicate poverty and malnutrition,” he said.
Professor Ken Norris, scientific director of ZL, said: “These alarming figures prove how quickly people change plants and animals in the oceans and represent a clear warning about the problems we may face as a result.”
Sea grass: extensive underwater "grasslands", which catch mineral-rich sediments and stabilize the seabed.
