Antidepressants taken during pregnancy do not affect the baby
Three new studies have found that taking antidepressants in pregnant women has no effect on the neuronal or behavioral development of their children.
Studies have shown that selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) have an increased risk of postpartum bleeding, but researchers have said that depression is an even greater risk for women and their children, so it needs to be treated.
“These studies add to a growing body of evidence regarding the safety of antidepressants during pregnancy,” John Thorp, deputy editor-in-chief of the International Journal of Obstetrics and Gynecology, said in a statement.
Although there are some increased risks, so far the evidence seems to show that the risks of untreated depression are higher than those of taking antidepressants.
The Norwegian Institute for Public Health coordinated a study on the motor development of children whose mothers were treated with SSRIs, analyzing data from 51,404 children from the Norwegian Mother and Child Cohort Study, researching the effects of using SSRIs to develop motor skills at age 3.
The researchers found that 381 mothers had used SSRIs during pregnancy, and 159 of them had been treated with drugs for an extended period.
Although exposure to SSRIs was associated to some extent with a delay in motor development, the researchers wrote in the study that the association “was not so significant as to attach clinical importance to delay.”
A group of researchers from the University of Adelaide in Australia conducted a data review for 49,000 women in the Danish National Birth Cohort to discover the effects of SSRIs on children’s behavior by age 7.
The study found that untreated depression in pregnant women was associated with an increased risk for behavioral problems.
In 210 of the children whose mothers had been treated for depression with SSRI, there was no increased risk of behavioral problems, compared to 231 children who were more prone to behavioral problems such as hyperactivity, inattention, and social problems.
The same group of Australian researchers also found in a separate study that mothers are more prone to bleeding after birth if treated with SSRIs.
Analysis of medical data from 30,198 who gave birth at a university hospital in Adelaide between 2002 and 2008 showed that the risk of postnatal bleeding increased by 5%, between 11-16%, if women were treated with SSRIs.
The risk of severe bleeding or postnatal anaemia has doubled, the researchers reported.
The researchers said that while the study linked SSRIs with increased risk, there are a large number of variables – from medications taken during birth to the limited amount of information researchers have about women’s specific medical conditions – that could have had an effect on bleeding potential.
“It is possible that women who took antidepressants at an advanced stage of pregnancy were those with the most serious stage of the disease, and this is the reason for the increased risk of postnatal bleeding, not antidepressants,” says Dr. Luke Grzeskowiak, a professor at Adelaide University.
On the basis of this study alone, we do not recommend that women stop taking anti-depressant medications during pregnancy, but that they be closely monitored to minimize the risk of potential bleeding.
