The Asia Pacific region already has the largest number of very wealthy people, named in the High Net Worth Individuals jargon, HNWI, with 4.69 million such individuals in 2014, up from 4.68 million in North America.
HNWI are people who can invest at least a million dollars, regardless of the value of real estate and other possessions.
“In the future, HNWI’s wealth is expected to grow more in Asia Pacific than in any other region of the world, with most of the new wealth coming from the emerging economies of China, India, Indonesia and Thailand,” said the study by Capgemini and RBC Wealth Management.
The report estimates that China and India account for nearly 10% of HNWI’s global wealth and are responsible for 17% of global new wealth growth after 2006.
China, the world’s second-largest economy after the United States, had $4.5 trillion in total wealth in 2014, up 17.5 percent and 19.3 percent, respectively, compared to 2013.
India has the fastest growth rate of the number of millionaires, 26.3%, up to 198,000 people, while their combined wealth has grown 28.2%, up to $785 billion.
