At the beginning of the school year
Yesterday, my eldest son, Stephan, started school.
Preparatory class, how he tries to improve the situation.
I do not know whether to rejoice or to let myself be overcome by melancholy; I am inclined, passively, to the second option.
First, because I feel like it’s only been three weeks, not three years since I first took him emotionally to the kindergarten.
Though he breathes a breath of relief, no normal parent is happy to raise his children.
Secondly, because I remember perfectly the same day of my childhood; then began a story that, to this day, has not ended.
I was not what is usually called a conscientious student.
On the contrary, I would say.
I have always liked school.
So much so that I chose to keep going, even as a teacher.
When I decided this was what I wanted to do my whole life, I knew it wasn’t an easy job.
And none with any stakes.
That’s because, like each one of us, I’ve come across all kinds of teachers: better or worse, more sympathetic or unbearable, smarter or really stupid.
Unfortunately, there are also people with other callings in this fold.
I think they’re toxic, because it hurts the enthusiasm and even the mind of a young man willing to form.
I was lucky enough to give, while I was a student or student, over a few, few, exceptional teachers.
These meetings can be decisive if they happen at the right time.
Whoever thinks that the role of the chair is the trivial transmission of information is wrong.
This can be done by anyone; to be informed, you can inform the student very well on your own, that we only live in the era of transparency.
A good teacher shapes the minds of students.
It shapes them, molds their thinking.
Sitting at the chair is not a privilege, as I think it is, but a great responsibility.
Young people are very hot-tempered, demanding, unforgiving, and always willing to look for the hibels of those in their lives.
It dictates their age, their temperament.
In adolescence, we all thought we knew everything, that we had unwavering certainty about everything.
When we grow up, we come to realize that we have only doubts.
That’s why the role of a teacher is to get the teenager out of their category of self-reliance and make them think.
That is, to learn to doubt, to ask questions.
Find out the answers on your own, both provisionally and provisionally.
Get involved in everything you do.
Discreetly point it at profitable models.
It is very difficult, especially since most of the time the student thinks that the teacher is his enemy.
One who can't wait to catch his foot wrongly to punish him.
But this justifies him, the one who is always misunderstood, rebellious, who owes it to live his age’s callings fully, to look at the one at the chair with suspicion.
He just can't naturally accept his attempt to order it.
Adolescents do not let themselves be put to the test, they do not accept restrictions.
Or if I give the impression that they are doing it, they take revenge somehow.
And, unfortunately, when there is a rigid person at the chair, who imposes himself through hardness and does not communicate, the students take revenge on the object taught.
There are thousands of such teenagers who miss meetings with great writers, for example, because of the lack of tact of the Romanian teacher.
There are thousands of such students who feel that history is a string of data, that mathematics is all that can be more tiring for their unripe mind.
I always urge my students: if you come across a teacher you don’t swallow, who can’t communicate from man to man with you, don’t let him take you away from the literature to which he should direct you.
How did I become a teacher myself?
I had a very good teacher in the 6th and 8th grades.
He opened my mind to some texts that spoke to the puberty of his time.
In high school, I met a university professor who opened the door to his library.
I was looking at him like a man from another world: he had the walls of the house covered with thick shelves of books.
I was lost in his library and dreamed of having one too.
I might have it now, but if I hadn't gotten him out of my way, I might have decided to become a footballer.
Or an engineer or a lawyer or who else knows what.
I don't think such meetings are accidental.
I don't believe in hazard.
It is essential to meet the man who takes you by the hand and patiently direct you to your own vocation.
And this is, most of the time, the teacher.
Now, my experience helps me to just talk about what it means to teach literature.
Literature cannot be taught.
There is no teacher of literature, as there is a teacher of mathematics.
How to fix the ineffable in concepts?
You know it, at most, approximate, without claiming to convey petrified truths.
The one at the chair can at most guide the reading, that’s quite different.
But above all it can be occasions of miraculous encounters, between a reader and some books.
There are meetings that can change the life of the one in the bank.
There are meetings that can open his mind, that can lift, as someone says, the scales from his eyes.
Therefore, the literature teacher must, first of all, be able to make his students understand (feel) that between literature and life there is no divorce.
On the contrary!
A great couser, Al. Paleologu, said something only seemingly paradoxical: “How much literature, so many, not vice versa!” and he was right.
That is why a good teacher prepares you for life, does not make you a specialist in an open field.
Fortunately, we always have something to learn.
And we, the teachers, or especially we, the teachers.
Most of the time, a great truth is repeated only out of inertia: not only do the disciples have to learn from their masters, but also vice versa.
Ideally, the teacher should be a master and the student an apprentice.
Who, like any valuable young man, leaves his master when he discovers his own path.
Few find it, it's fair.
But it was the master who lit the spark.
There is no greater happiness for a pure-blood teacher than to endure as many separations as possible.
