Extending the Fifa investigation
U.S. and Swiss courts will face new arrests
The U.S. and Swiss authorities have announced that they will start criminal prosecutions of new individuals and organizations as part of an investigation into corruption in FIFA.
U.S. Justice Minister Loretta Lynch announced at a press conference in Zurich on Monday that the area of investigations into corruption in world football has been widened.
“Based on our cooperation and new evidence, we will pursue additional criminal prosecutions against new individuals and new organizations,” Lynch said.
In May, several senior FIFA officials were arrested in Switzerland in this corruption case.
Many of them have already been extradited to the United States.
“We have hopes that other people who are being prosecuted will also arrive in the U.S.,” Lynch added.
Switzerland’s attorney general, Michael Lauber, also present at the press conference, said his institution had seized several assets, including housing and land in the Alps, as well as financial assets, as part of an investigation conducted in collaboration with the US.
“We haven’t even reached the end of the first half,” Lauber said.
So far, a huge amount of information has been confiscated, 11 terrabytes.
At the same time, 121 bank accounts are being investigated.
A media rights transfer contract was also brought to the attention of investigators at the 2010 World Cups in South Africa and 2014 – Brazil.
FIFA is facing a major corruption scandal after the U.S. judiciary indicted 14 people, including two FIFA vice-presidents and many FIFA officials.
Detainees are being investigated for bribery and other benefits from the early 1990s to the present, totaling more than $150 million.
In the aftermath of the scandal, Swiss President Joseph Blatter announced in early July that he was stepping down as FIFA president after being re-elected for the fifth time.
