At the Craiova Detention Center the youngest student is 15 years old and is in class I
Justice Minister Robert Cazanciuc said at the opening of the school year at the Craiova Detention Center that the youngest student is 15 and is in first class, and the oldest is 25 and is in eleventh class, showing that they could have another life if they went to school.
I chose to participate in the opening of the school year in a center belonging to the National Administration of Penitentiaries to try to draw attention, and in this way, to lesser-known realities.
The youngest student, aged 15, is enrolled in Class I, and the oldest is 25 years old and enrolled in Class XI.
"There are complicated topics that society is concerned to discuss at this time, all of us are weighed down by our own concerns and problems, but we must not overlook the lesson that many over 100 young people from the Craiova Detention Center offer," Minister Robert Cazanciuc said Monday at the school year's opening celebration.
The Minister of Justice drew attention to the fact that the lack of education, motivated in many cases by the lack of material possibilities, can lead to tragedies, stating that young people in this center would have had another chance in life if they could have followed the natural school course of any child, if they had had the opportunity to teach us not only to write, to read, but also to receive moral values.
“The role of the penitentiary system is not to permanently isolate people who have broken the law from society, to lock them behind high walls, but to try to re-educate and prepare them, so that when they return to the community they have more chances of reintegration,” added Cazanciuc.
The minister said that it is necessary to invest in schools, hospitals, roads, but also in the prison system, because in many cases the conditions of detention are at the limit of humanity and because, in the absence of money and personnel, it will be difficult to talk about the reinstatement of convicted persons.
We collaborate very well with the Ministry of Education and thanks to this partnership, every year, in the penitentiary system, there are more than 2000 graduates of school training courses.
Of course, we won’t be able to change overnight what hasn’t been done for 25 years, but there are important steps we’re taking.
"In all these steps we also need the support of society, and this support can only come if we demonstrate that we are doing our duty, that through your work many young people have a chance and do not pose a danger to society," Cazanciuc said.
The Minister of Justice wished success to both students and educators, showing that success comes only through the combined efforts of all.
“And because today is the feast of the Ascension of the Holy Cross, I would invite all students and teachers to visit the mausoleums of Soveja, Maresti and beyond, to understand what it means to fight young people for ideals,” said Cazanciuc.
