ZDI: Why didn’t you leave Iași to work in an IT company abroad?
Andrei Postolache: The reasons are rather sentimental and emotional.
I was away on many short business trips, I also lived a year in Cluj.
I came back every time, because I knew this was my home.
ZDI: Why did you decide now to set up a political party?
Andrei Postolache: Now that we have reached a certain maturity, we are a group of people who have been dating for some time.
We met in professional contexts, we started discussing how we could get involved.
At first, we became more timid, involved in smaller things, with NGO projects, various building or charitable actions, and somehow things evolved naturally and organically, and now it happened to be the time when we came to the decision that we had to get more involved than that.
ZDI: Name three concrete projects to make the work of local public administration more efficient!
Andrei Postolache: The first project consists of a minimum computerization of the activity of the city hall so that the different departments, institutions and kings collaborate as best as possible.
But more importantly, to be able to publish transparent data about the activities carried out in detail: budgets, reports, projects, etc. We are talking about informational organization.
The second would be transparency because this leads to efficiency.
If you have a project in a particular neighborhood, it is important to consult the public with the affected people.
If we talk about efficiency, we must not forget the public transport, we have the worst buses in the country.
New means of transport must be purchased.
ZDI: Nowadays, the image of a city is extremely important.
How would you promote Iași?
Andrei Postolache: You get on the plane and you’re looking for investors in this world.
There are conferences, industry events in which you can "sell" the city.
You have to want to do it and know how to do it.
And here we have an advantage: we come from the business and we brought customers to Iași.
ZDI: What is the brand of Iasi?
Andrei Postolache: My opinion is that we have to be a city of technology, one way or the other.
We already have the IT industry, and we need to expand it, go into medicine, go into robotics, go into 3D printing, go on in that spirit and unite such elements.
I think the brand should be in the area of science, I mean here the modern brand of the city.
Of course, Iași already has a historic brand that must not be changed, namely cultural life.
I see the two elements in balance: culture and technology.
ZDI: How will you compensate for the lack of experience in public administration, as well as the lack of traditional party structures with which elections are still being won in Romania?
Andrei Postolache: Administration is a form of management, which means organization, planning, communication, working with people and carrying out projects.
We have experience in management.
We don’t want traditional structures, we don’t care.
We want to engage people, we’ll talk to everyone, we won’t just stay on Facebook, we’re not an online party.
We don't want to have "volunteers" brought in by bus.
That means we rely on people who really want to get involved and help, and we think there are enough of them.
ZDI: Should the mayor of Iași be more concerned with promoting the image of the city nationally and internationally, or is it necessary that the area of concern is always of a building nature?
Andrei Postolache: One without the other does not work.
First you have to solve today’s problems, the emergencies.
But if you don’t make your city known, if you don’t attract money into your city, at some point you will run out of money and you won’t be able to make, for example, streets.
You have to do both at the same time and you have to have competent people beside you.
The mayor doesn’t have to do everything.
We must abandon the model of the mayor-father, who comes and beats with the punch in the mass and solves everything.
Oh, no.
We're a team.
The mayor is the conductor of an orchestra.
ZDI: Will you try to attract IT business people who can financially support the party?
Andrei Postolache: We are looking for people who want to do something right, have an unblemished reputation, be clearly integrity and be honorable.
From this point of view, we have no other filters.
We're not looking for three people with money, we're looking for 10,000 people, or, why not, 300,000, who want to get involved and do something for everyone.
