The red flag was raised.
Labour’s internal ballot seems more spectacular and politically significant, as the newly elected leader automatically becomes its spearhead in the upcoming elections.
Rise, therefore, the red-lighted flag / Under its folds we shall live and die.
That's what Jeremy Corbyn played in the London Sanctuary House pub yesterday.
He testified to many facts and oaths / Let us not change his color now.
Readers who do not know the melodic line of this unofficial anthem of the British and international left (The Red Flag) can search it on the internet and would not be excluded from having a surprise.
With our heads uncovered, let us all swear that we will wear it until we collapse.
The author of these lines is not at all an admirer of the red flags (and those who wave them), but he respects the democratic political traditions built around them.
If Jeremy Corbyn manages to unite yesterday’s left with tomorrow’s, this love story between himself and the Labour base will have a happy-end.
I don’t think it will happen that way, but it seems premature to talk about the great and inevitable electoral defeat, in five years’ time, of a leader elected yesterday.
Now, however, we can refer to the procedures: we have witnessed a democratic exercise of impressive scope.
British Labour did not invent the system of direct voting for the party leader among the western left.
The French Socialists have been practicing for several years a more complicated, motif-based system that allows the expression of all members and sympathizers; in addition, they have organized a preliminary competition for the nomination of the presidential candidate since 2012.
However, Labour’s internal ballot seems more spectacular and politically significant, as the newly elected leader automatically becomes its spearhead in the upcoming elections.
It is, of course, also a matter of political system, with the customization of power being more pronounced in Britain than on the other side of the English Channel.
In addition, voter turnout was high in all three "circles": the members themselves, members of trade unions and other party-affiliated organizations, and finally the group of supporters (who received the ballot after a brief registration procedure).
This last group gives us interesting insights into the perceptions of the left-wing segments of British society, especially those made up of young or middle-aged people, educated, interested in the political phenomenon.
Many of them will choose to get even more involved in the future, precisely because of the signal offered by Corbyn’s victory.
There is, as far as I know, no sociological inquiry that tells us too much about the attitudes of this Labour “outside circle,” so cautious speculation is permissible.
I think we encounter enough attitudes similar to those of Podemos sympathizers (Spain) or even SYRIZA (Greece), with the observation that they will go through the traditional channels of the left.
If we want to identify a “anti-system” vocation, it is reflected primarily in the rejection of the centrist line, New Labour (for all, only a disguised form of thatcherism).
The second component would be the repudiation of the leaders considered guilty of the two successive electoral failures, one of the arguments being that they did not go far enough to the left, that they did not delineate themselves firmly from the Tony Blair era.
The second landmark - in my opinion, and more suggestively - is offered by the recent Scottish independence referendum.
If we abstract from the separatist message and focus strictly on aspirations in relation to other political themes, we see how Scottish nationalists have captured the energies of pro-social-state segments of the public, driven by the aspiration for equity, adept at disarmament and hostile to military involvement abroad, but also sensitive to the new themes of the Left: ecology, assistance, and generosity.
The Scottish Labours thus lost an electorate to which they should have had, at least in principle, privileged access, but which they can now recover (see their enthusiasm for Corbyn’s campaign).
Such energies exist all over the UK, but the old leadership could not attract them.
Jeremy Corbyn, with his vocation as an outsider, has more chances of success than Ed Miliband, the Labour aristocrat.
The comparison with Scotland tells us more, I think, than the leftist anti-system in the southern periphery of Europe.
The term "anti-system" is too harsh: "anti-establishment" seems more appropriate to me.
By next week we will learn more about Jeremy Corbyn’s first steps as an opposition leader.
We will see if the red flag does not resound in the House of Commons (it would not be for the first time), after the new leader has taken his place, primarily of the opposition banks.
However, what Jeremy Corbyn wants now from his colleagues in Parliament is primarily unity - and he really has reason to be concerned about it.
